{
  "title": "Testing Strategies for Warnings Code with pytest (Python 3.12+)",
  "summary": "This explainer outlines the best practices and methods to test warnings generated by your code effectively using the pytest framework in Python 3.12+.",

  "key_points": [
    "Importing necessary modules: `pytest`, `pytest-warnings`",
    "Using the `@pytest.mark.warns(regex=r'expected warning message')` to mark the test that should assert a specific warning",
    "Employing monkeypatching to control the warnings generated by your code during testing",
    "Utilizing the `assert_warns()`, `assert_warns_once_with()`, and `assert_raises_warning()` functions for various warning assertion needs",
    "Incorporating custom plugins, like `pytest-warnings-plus`, to expand your testing capabilities"
  ],

  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "import pytest\nfrom pytest_warnings import assert_warns, warns\n\ndef function_with_warning():\n    warning = UserWarning('This is a custom user warning')\n    warn(warning, UserWarning)\n\n@pytest.mark.warns(match='This is a custom user warning', raise_on=UserWarning)\ndef test_function_with_warning():\n    assert function_with_warning() == UserWarning('This is a custom user warning')"
    },
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "import pytest\nfrom your_module import YourClass\n\n@pytest.mark.usefixtures(\'monkeypatch\')\ndef test_your_class(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setattr(YourClass, 'method_that_generates_warning', lambda self: warn('Warning generated by method'))\n    # Test your code using the modified class"
    }
  ],

  "version_notes": [
    "Note that pytest-warnings (v6.0) is compatible with Python 3.12+",
    "It's essential to check the latest version of pytest and its plugins for any new features or compatibility updates"
  ],

  "caveats": [
    "While pytest offers powerful tools for testing warnings, it's crucial to remember that tests should not be overly reliant on specific warning messages as they can change during development",
    "Ensure your test cases cover both expected and unexpected warnings (e.g., exceptions or errors) generated by your code"
  ]
}
